Exercise 2: Calculation of the absorption spectrum of benzene molecule (C6H6) using
            the turbo_davidson.x code

 Step 1. Run the SCF ground-state calculation

    mpirun -np 4 /scratch/timrov/QE_tmp7_6.0/qe-6.0/bin/pw.x < Benzene.scf.in > Benzene.scf.out

 Step 2. Run the turboDavidson calculation in the Independent Particle Approximation

    mpirun -np 4 /scratch/timrov/QE_tmp7_6.0/qe-6.0/bin/turbo_davidson.x < Benzene.davidson.no_int.in > Benzene.davidson.no_int.out

 Step 3. Run the spectrum calculation

    /scratch/timrov/QE_tmp7_6.0/qe-6.0/bin/turbo_spectrum.x < Benzene.tddfpt_pp.in > Benzene.tddfpt_pp.out

 Step 4. Plot the spectrum using "gnuplot" and the script "plot_spectrum.gnu". 
         Since the interaction was switched off, you should obtain the same spectrum 
         as the one obtained using the epsilon.x code in the exercise1.

    gnuplot -> load 'plot_spectrum.gnu'

    evince Benzene_spectrum.eps

 Step 5. Switch on the electronic interaction (Hartree and Exchange-Correlation) 
         and see how changes the absorption spectrum of benzene.
         
     mpirun -np 4 /scratch/timrov/QE_tmp7_6.0/qe-6.0/bin/turbo_davidson.x < Benzene.davidson.with_int.in > Benzene.davidson.with_int.out

 Step 6. Run the spectrum calculation (optional)
         In the file 'Benzene.tddfpt_pp.in' set  eign_file = 'Benzene.eigen' !!!

    /scratch/timrov/QE_tmp7_6.0/qe-6.0/bin/turbo_spectrum.x < Benzene.tddfpt_pp.in > Benzene.tddfpt_pp.out

 Step 7. Plot the spectrum using "gnuplot" and the script "plot_spectrum.gnu".
         In the script 'plot_spectrum.gnu' change the title to 'turbo-davidson.x (interacting electrons)'

     gnuplot -> load 'plot_spectrum.gnu'

     evince Benzene_spectrum.eps

